The '''''Redemption'' scenario''' was a [[Flight simulator/Legends|training scenario]] used for [[New Republic/Legends|New Republic]] [[Pilot/Legends|pilot]] trainees, particularly [[Rogue Squadron/Legends|Rogue Squadron]] hopefuls; its difficulty led many who flew in it to nickname it the '''''Requiem'' scenario'''.

==Historical scenario==
{{Quote|I barely made it through that one. I was sure that the Korolev was a goner.''"<br />"''We've analyzed your performance, lieutenant, and it was nearly flawless. Either you were very lucky or your skills are improving. Either way, we're thankful for your efforts. There's nothing more to add.''"<br />"''I suppose I could have attacked the Warspite.''"<br />"''Let's just stay alive, shall we?|[[Keyan Farlander/Legends|Keyan Farlander]] is debriefed by [[Lagrane]]|<ref name="X-Wing: The Official Strategy Guide">''[[X-Wing: The Official Strategy Guide]]''</ref>}}
The ''Redemption'' scenario was based on an [[Skirmish near Brigia|incident]] in [[Alliance to Restore the Republic/Legends|Rebel]] history which took place shortly after the [[Battle of Brigia (Galactic Civil War)|Battle of Brigia]]. Several [[Lambda-class T-4a shuttle/Legends|shuttles]], along with the [[CR90 corvette/Legends|CR90 corvette]] ''[[Korolev]]'' were transferring wounded personnel to the [[EF76 Nebulon-B escort frigate/Legends|EF76 Nebulon-B escort frigate]] [[Redemption/Legends|''Redemption'']]. The [[Galactic Empire/Legends|Imperial]] Nebulon-B frigate [[Warspite (EF76 Nebulon-B escort frigate)|''Warspite'']] dropped out of [[Hyperspace/Legends|hyperspace]] and launched [[TIE series/Legends|TIE Series]] fighters. It then jumped to hyperspace again, emerging on the other side of the transfer and launching more fighters. The defending Rebel [[T-65 X-wing starfighter/Legends|X-wings]] had moved to intercept the first wave and were out of position for the second wave. Historically, the pilots of [[Red Squadron (Rebel Alliance)/Legends|Red Squadron]], particularly [[Keyan Farlander/Legends|Keyan Farlander]], were able to evade the [[TIE/ln space superiority starfighter/Legends|TIE/LN starfighters]] long enough to destroy both waves of [[TIE/sa tactical bomber/Legends|TIE/sa bombers]] and all Rebel ships escaped successfully.

Key to their success was Farlander's decision to use his [[Proton torpedo/Legends|proton torpedoes]] to destroy the first wave of TIE Bombers quickly, along with ignoring the threat of the TIE Fighters, which were attacking the X-wings themselves, until all TIE Bombers had been destroyed.

==Simulation==
The difficulty of preventing the multiple TIE Bomber groups from launching proton torpedoes at the ''Korolev'' made the mission an ideal choice for a training simulation. In the simulation, pilot trainees could fly as either the Rebel defenders or the Imperial aggressors. The sides typically consisted of four Rebel pilots and as many as a dozen Imperial pilots, making any Rebel pilot to accomplish their goal and still survive a truly skilled flyer.

In the simulator, the Rebel pilots were instructed to defend the frigate from the TIEs. If they were not careful, the ''Warspite'' could move further in system and join in the attack, however they were free to experiment with their strategy. Meanwhile those piloting the Imperial fighters were restricted to the original strategy and much of their initial run sequence was preprogrammed.

==Strategy==
{{Quote|By the book, or are we doing something fancy?''"<br />"''By the book. Keep the home fires burning and pick up after me.|[[Nawara Ven]] and [[Corran Horn/Legends|Corran Horn]] decide on strategy|<ref name="X-Wing: Rogue Squadron">''[[X-Wing: Rogue Squadron]]''</ref>}}
The textbook strategy was to send a single X-wing to confront the first wave of TIEs, while the other three remained as close support for the transfer. This would result in the ''Warspite'' launching subsequent waves from a large distance rather than putting itself at unnecessary risk. If all fighters moved off to confront the first wave before ''Warspite'' entered hyperspace, as had happened originally, the ''Warspite'' would return much closer to the ''Korolev'' making subsequent waves much harder to reach before they could launch torpedoes. Only when the ''Warspite'' was in hyperspace would it be safe for all X-wings to move out to engage.

The weakness of this strategy was that it forced a single X-wing to deal with five fighters at once, two TIE Fighters and three TIE Bombers. That same X-wing would then have to turn right round to confront the next wave from a different direction. However, most other strategies proved disastrous.

Farlander's technique became a favorite for the single pilot, using proton torpedoes to target the bombers, and then mixing it up with the starfighters. This technique recognized that only the bombers could hurt the two vulnerable capital ships with their torpedoes. [[Corran Horn/Legends|Corran Horn]] was known to be one survivor of the scenario, by using a variation on this technique in which he initially engaged with lasers and used torpedoes to destroy any bombers that made it past him before they could get into launch range. Among the bomber pilots "killed" was Horn's rival [[Bror Jace]].

==Behind the scenes==
This event is mentioned in the book ''[[X-Wing: Rogue Squadron]]'', however it is based on an actual mission level from the game [[Star Wars: X-Wing (video game)|''Star Wars: X-Wing'']]. The strategies recommended in the book are, in fact, actual strategies used in the level.

